snippet.textDisplay: Thanks for posting this, Jeff. I'm in NYC; gyms (and many other things) closed Monday night (March 16th) and we're looking at further restrictions for who knows how long. I tried out the A set today. Had to make modifications to even some of the beginner exercises, was unable to do some for the full minute, and only did one round (perhaps this routine wasn't created with 50-year-old women in mind?), but I'm really happy to have something to supplement my outdoor runs (which may become indoor rope jumping). I've worked hard over the decades to build and, especially important at my age, maintain strength and lean body mass. This should help. Also, the discipline of this workout extends to all sorts of other things that help structure days that for so many of us have become chaotic, panicky, or at the very least, flabby.

snippet.textDisplay: Thank you so much for this! Could you do a video on exertion headaches? I know Jesse has mentioned them being a symptom of his brain injuries but I've never had those kind of injuries (that I know of) and I've suddenly started to get a pounding headache during the first or second exercise of every workout. Sometimes, even in the warm-up. This is after years of weight training with no headaches. I've read a lot about it. I make sure I'm well hydrated, I'm breathing properly (I think) and I try to keep my neck stretched and loose during exercises. I'd really love to know what Jeff can tell us about this issue. I know (based on my research) that I'm far from the only person that suffers from this. Unfortunately, no one has any great advice on how to deal with it.
